  "text": "The InventoryConsumer implementation follows patterns established in the Apache Kafka codebase (sg-evals/kafka--0753c489).\n\n1. ConsumerConfig constants: Referenced from examples/src/main/java/kafka/examples/Consumer.java (createKafkaConsumer method, lines 127-148) and tools/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/tools/TransactionalMessageCopier.java (createConsumer method, lines 205-221). Both use ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG, ConsumerConfig.AUTO_OFFSET_RESET_CONFIG, ConsumerConfig.KEY_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, and ConsumerConfig.VALUE_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG instead of raw string literals.\n\n2. poll(Duration) API: The KafkaConsumer.java Javadoc (lines 188-237) and examples show consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100)) and consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(1000)) as the standard polling pattern. The deprecated poll(long timeout) is explicitly avoided.\n\n3. commitSync() after each batch: The KafkaConsumer.java Manual Offset Control example (lines 216-237) shows calling consumer.commitSync() after processing each batch of records with enable.auto.commit=false. The Consumer.java example also calls consumer.commitSync() after handling offset resets.\n\n4. WakeupException for clean shutdown: Both TransactionalMessageCopier.java (lines 354-413) and Consumer.java demonstrate the shutdown pattern: call consumer.wakeup() from another thread, catch WakeupException in the poll loop, and ignore it only when the consumer is intentionally closing (using a closed/isShuttingDown flag)."
